{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519959"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:18:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:18:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13115"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13115"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.07,0.79,0.06,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5552"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64692"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5552"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13115"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50126"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10361"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10427"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17635"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64692"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department by his wife due to altered mental status over the past 24 hours. He has a medical history of alcohol-related cirrhosis and previous variceal bleeding requiring hospitalisation one year ago. He continues to drink alcohol regularly. His wife reports he has become increasingly confused and is not behaving like his usual self.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.3\u00b0C. He is rousable but disoriented to place and time. He appears cachectic with prominent abdominal wall veins, spider naevi across the trunk, and significant ascites. When the patient extends his arms out in front of him, a jerking movement of the limbs is observed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 8.3 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAspartate transaminase: 89 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlanine transaminase: 112 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal bilirubin: 78 \u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin: 22 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAmmonia: 120 \u00b5mol/L (11-32)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Furosemide","Rifaximin","Lactulose","Octreotide","Carvedilol"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with hepatic encephalopathy, evidenced by altered mental status and asterixis, in the setting of decompensated cirrhosis (demonstrated by spider naevi, caput medusae, and ascites). Hepatic encephalopathy occurs when the liver fails to convert ammonia to urea, leading to toxin accumulation. The elevated ammonia level of 120 \u00b5mol/L supports the diagnosis, though it remains primarily a clinical diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELactulose\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line treatment for hepatic encephalopathy. This non-absorbable disaccharide is metabolised by gut bacteria into acidic compounds that convert absorbable ammonia into non-absorbable ammonium, facilitating its excretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERifaximin\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-absorbable antibiotic which alters the gut microbiota. It has been found to be effective in treating hepatic encephalopathy and provides better remission when combined with lactulose. However, it is typically used as an add-on therapy when lactulose alone provides inadequate response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat fluid overload in decompensated liver disease. While this patient has ascites, diuretics are often temporarily discontinued during episodes of encephalopathy until mental status and electrolytes stabilise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOctreotide\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for acute variceal bleeding. While this patient has a history of variceal bleeding, there are no current symptoms of bleeding to suggest this as the precipitant of his encephalopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarvedilol \u003C/strong\u003Eis a non-selective beta-blocker used for primary and secondary prevention of variceal bleeding in cirrhosis. While it may be considered in the context of this patient\u0027s history, it is not indicated for acute hepatic encephalopathy and is therefore not the main management priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to pharmacological management of the patient\u0027s hepatic encephalopathy, potential causes of this episode must be investigated for and treated. Common precipitants include gastrointestinal bleeding, electrolyte derangements, constipation, infection and drugs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lactulose is first-line treatment for hepatic encephalopathy as it enables excretion of ammonia through gut acidification","Clinical features of hepatic encephalopathy include altered mental status, and asterixis"],"references":["Montagnese S, Rautou PE, Romero-G\u00f3mez M, Larsen FS, Shawcross DL, Thabut D, et al. EASL Clinical Practice Guidelines on the management of hepatic encephalopathy. Journal of Hepatology. 2022 Sep 1;77(3):807\u201324. Available at https://www.journal-of-hepatology.eu/article/S0168-8278(22)00346-4/fulltext","Ferenci P. Hepatic encephalopathy in adults: Treatment. [Upated 2023 Oct]. UpToDate (Runyon, BA, Ed., Eds.), UpToDate, Waltham, MA. 2015. https://www.uptodate.com/contents/hepatic-encephalopathy-in-adults-treatment"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50126"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13115"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50126"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T15:23:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T15:24:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5552"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64692"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","positi